column38:
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center is an investor in private equity. The portfolio is split between venture capital, primary, and
secondary funds. Cambridge Associates acts as an advisor to the endowment plan.
column39:
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center holds a preference for buyout, co-investment multi-manager, distressed debt, early stage,
early stage: seed, early stage: start-up, expansion / late stage, fund of funds, growth, mezzanine, natural resources, secondaries, and
venture vehicles. Geographically, it invests globally, with a particular focus on Asia and North America. It invests in a wide range of
industries, including business services, energy & utilities, industrials, information technology, diversified, healthcare, medical devices
& equipment, pharmaceuticals, and consumer services sectors. It typically invests USD 10 million per private equity vehicle. It is
willing to invest in first-time funds.

column38:
State of Wisconsin Investment Board is an investor in private equity. The public pension fund gains exposure to the asset class via
direct investments, primary and secondary fund commitments. It currently allocates 13.25% of its total investment portfolio to the
asset class. Its private equity portfolio is managed by StepStone Group. Callan Associates and NEPC act as advisors to the
public pension fund.
column39:
State of Wisconsin Investment Board holds a preference for balanced, buyout, co-investment, direct secondaries, distressed debt,
early stage, early stage: seed, early stage: start-up, expansion/late stage, fund of funds, growth, hybrid, mezzanine, natural
resources, secondaries, special situations, turnaround, and venture vehicles. Geographically, the public pension fund gains exposure
globally, including Americas, Asia, Australasia, emerging markets, Europe, Greater China, the Nordics, and OECD countries. It targets
diversified industries, including financial services, biopharmaceuticals, pharmaceutical research & development, oncology/cancer
treatment, diagnostic equipment, business services, consumer discretionary, energy & utilities, financial & insurance services,
healthcare, industrials, information technology, raw materials & natural resources, telecoms & media, diversified, business support
services, marketing/advertising, outsourcing, consumer products, education/training, food, retail, transportation services, travel &
leisure, oil & gas, power & utilities, renewable energy, insurance, biotechnology, healthcare, healthcare it, healthcare specialists,
medical devices & equipment, pharmaceuticals, aerospace, automobiles, other vehicles & parts, construction, defence,
environmental services, heating, cooling & ventilation equipment and services, industrial machinery, logistics & distribution,
hardware, internet, it infrastructure, it security/cybersecurity, software, agribusiness, forestry & timber, mining, information
services, media, telecoms, consumer services, packaging, digital media, medical software, beauty & hygiene, pet products,
recreational hobbies & sporting goods, accounting/finance software, hedge funds, analytics & performance software, non-alcoholic
beverages, restaurants & nightlife, private equity, public relations & communications, alcoholic beverages, hr & workforce software,
legal software, logistics software, accounting services, professional sports/esports, materials, gaming, and therapeutic
devices sectors.

column1: State Universities Retirement System of Illinois
column38:
State Universities Retirement System of Illinois will be committing USD 475 million to private equity as part of its 2025 pacing plan.
More information regarding preferences will be released after the pension's December 2024 Board Meeting.
column39:
State Universities Retirement System of Illinois holds a preference for balanced, buyout, co-investment, distressed debt, early stage,
early stage: seed, early stage: start-up, expansion / late stage, fund of funds, growth, mezzanine, natural resources, secondaries,
special situations, turnaround, venture debt, and venture (general) vehicles. Geographically, the public pension fund gains exposure
globally, including Africa, Asia, Australasia, emerging markets, Europe, Israel, North America and OECD countries. It targets
diversified industries, including business services, consumer discretionary, healthcare, industrials, and information technology
sectors. It typically commits between USD 25 million and USD 125 million per private equity vehicle. It is interested in first-time
funds. It considers separate account structures and committing to a fund before it has held its initial close.

column38:
MIT Investment Management Company is an investor in private equity. The endowment plan gains exposure to the asset class via
primary and secondary fund commitments.
column39:

early stage: start-up, expansion/late stage, fund of funds, natural resources, special situations, timber, turnaround, venture

healthcare, industrials, information technology, real estate, and telecoms & media sectors. It is interested in first-time funds.

column38:

Primary fund commitments, and secondary fund commitments.

column1: CalPERS - California Public Employees' Retirement System
column38:
CalPERS - California Public Employees' Retirement System is an investor in private equity. The public pension fund gains exposure to
the asset class via direct investments, primary fund commitments, and secondary fund commitments. It currently allocates 17% of
its total investment portfolio to the asset class, meeting its target allocation of 17%. Wilshire Associates acts as an advisor to the
public pension fund. Its private equity portfolio is managed by Abbott Capital Management, Cambridge Associates,
Meketa Investment Group, and Hamilton Lane.
column39:
CalPERS - California Public Employees' Retirement System holds a preference for balanced, early-stage, early-stage: seed, early-
stage: start-up, expansion / late stage, natural resources, bridge fund, buyout, secondaries, CLO, fund of funds, special situations, co-
investment, growth, timber, hybrid, turnaround, direct secondaries, venture debt, distressed debt, mezzanine, and venture vehicles.
Geographically, the public pension fund gains exposure globally, including Africa, Asia, Australasia, Europe, Greater China, Israel,
North America, the Nordics, ASEAN, BRIC, and OECD countries, and emerging markets. It targets diversified industries, including
business services, consumer discretionary, energy & utilities, healthcare, and information technology sectors. It typically commits
between USD 50 million and USD 500 million per private equity vehicle. It is interested in first-time funds, separate account
structures, and committing to a fund before it has held its initial close.

column38:
Harvard Management Company (HMC) is an investor in private equity. It currently allocates 39% of its total assets under
management to the asset class. All of its investment decisions are conducted in-house.
column39:
Harvard Management Company does not have a preference for any sector, location, or fund type but strives to maintain a diverse
and extensive private equity portfolio. The majority of its investments are to US and European buyout and venture capital vehicles,
although it does also invest in Asia and other emerging markets. HMC’s target return is 500 basis points higher than the Cambridge
Associates US Venture Capital Index. HMC typically commits between USD 25 million and USD 200 million per fund. It will invest in
first-time funds if managed by a spin-off team, will invest in separate accounts, and will consider investing in a fund before it has
held the first close, though this is not an important part of its investment strategy.

column38:
TIAA is an investor in private equity. The asset manager gains exposure to the asset class via direct investments, primary fund
commitments, and secondary fund commitments including venture capital. It currently allocates less than 1% of its total assets to
the asset class.
column39:
TIAA holds a preference for balanced, buyout, co-investment, early-stage, fund of funds, growth, and venture vehicles.
Geographically, the private sector pension fund gains exposure globally, including Africa, Asia, Australasia, BRIC countries,
Caribbean, Central America, Central and East Europe, East and Southeast Asia, emerging markets, Europe, Greater China, Midwest,
North America, Northeast, OECD countries, South America, South Asia, Southeast, and West Europe. It targets a wide range of
industries, including agribusiness, public relations & communications, e-financial, sales & marketing software, emarketing/digital
marketing, web applications, packaging, consumer services, telecoms, media, commercial property, chemicals, software, IT
infrastructure, internet, hardware, ship building & repair, rail transport, logistics & distribution, environmental services, defence,
aerospace, pharmaceuticals, medical devices & equipment, healthcare IT, healthcare, biotechnology, financial services, renewable
energy, oil & gas, retail, food, education/training, consumer products, business support services, information technology, industrials,
energy & utilities, business services, analytics & performance software, application integration software, content management
software, digital brokerage, manufacturing, real estate tech, artificial intelligence, saas, fintech, cloud computing, and diversified
sectors. It considers first-time managers in situations where the partners have managed funds and have a good track record and
under circumstances that offer the opportunity to invest in a specific sector or targeted region. It is interested in distressed debt
vehicles and will not invest in mezzanine vehicles because it operates its direct mezzanine program. It typically commits between
USD 20 million and USD 200 million per private equity fund.

column39:

OECD countries, Africa, Asia, Asia and Rest of World, Australasia, the Caribbean, East and Southeast Asia, the EU, Europe, Greater
China, Israel, Middle East, the Nordics, North America, South America, South Asia, Southeast, West Europe, and emerging markets. It
targets a wide range of industries, including business services, consumer discretionary, energy & utilities, financial & insurance
services, and healthcare sectors. It typically commits between USD 150 million and USD 300 million per private equity vehicle. It is
interested in first-time funds and separate account structures. However, it is not interested in committing to a fund before it has
held its initial close.

column1: Pennsylvania Public School Employees' Retirement System
column38:
Pennsylvania Public School Employees' Retirement System is an investor in private equity. The public pension fund gains exposure to

portfolio to the asset class, above its target allocation of 12%. Its private equity portfolio is managed by Hamilton Lane. Verus
Investments acts as an advisor to the public pension fund.
column39:
Pennsylvania Public School Employees' Retirement System holds a preference for balanced, bridge fund, buyout, CLO, co-
investment, distressed debt, early stage, expansion/late stage, fund of funds, growth, hybrid, mezzanine, natural resources,
secondaries, special situations, timber, turnaround, venture and venture debt strategies. Geographically, the public pension fund
gains exposure globally, including Africa, Asia, Australasia, the Caribbean, Europe, Greater China, North America, Israel, the Nordics,
emerging markets, ASEAN, and OECD countries. It targets diversified industries, including power & utilities, real estate, raw materials
& natural resources, information technology, industrials, healthcare, and financial & insurance service sectors. It typically commits
between USD 75 million and USD 200 million per private equity vehicle. It is interested in first-time funds, separate account
structures, and committing to a fund before it has held its initial close.

column38:
NPS will invest in private equity over the coming year. The public pension scheme’s Asia Private Equity Investment Team will invest
KRW 1.2 trillion across four domestic private equity funds and four domestic venture capital funds. It will select private equity
managers in July 2024 and venture capital managers in November 2024. For private equity, the institution is open to both primary
and secondary strategies, as well as co-investments if the requested commitment amount is above KRW 200 billion with no fee and
no carry condition. Within venture capital, it is open to all venture stages. The South Korea-based investor will select its domestic
fund managers via RFP.
Regarding overseas investments, NPS will continue to invest with a global outlook and a wide range of strategies across diverse
industries. The institution will focus on value-adding investments, secondaries, and search for private equity managers specialized in
middle-market deals. The pension fund is open to investing with both new and existing managers.
column39:
National Pension Service (NPS) holds a preference for buyout, growth, secondary, venture capital, co-investment strategies.
Geographically, the public pension fund's private equity portfolio is split 20.2% to domestic investments and 79.8% to overseas,
including North America (24%), Europe (14.8%), Asia and emerging countries in South America (5.05%), and global (35.9%). It has
partnerships with more than 100 private equity firms globally. It targets a wide range of industries, including business services,
financial services, energy, consumer services, healthcare, and technology sectors.
NPS gains exposure to the asset management company’s equity through its investments in commingled funds targeting the fund
management companies. The institution invests in fund managers to strengthen its partnership with GPs and negotiating power in
terms of management fees and investment opportunities.
NPS deploys between KRW 30 billion and KRW 60 billion per domestic venture capital fund. For private equity funds, it typically
allocates between KRW 100 billion and KRW 350 billion per onshore fund and between USD 100 million and USD 200 million per
offshore fund. It may stretch its ticket size on a case-by-case basis. The institution is open to investing through separate accounts
and expects the use of such investments to increase in the longer term. The public pension scheme acts as a first-close investor but
will not invest with first-time managers. It prefers GPs who have a demonstrable record of providing investment returns above the
second quartile. The company also prefers managers who maintain price discipline. When deciding on investments, NPS takes
environmental and social factors into consideration.
NPS is also a direct investor in the asset class. The institution deems its private equity direct investment activities to increase going
forward. It also gains access to the asset class through Corporate Partnership Funds (COPA Funds) established by NPS and South
Korean conglomerates, such as Samsung, Hyundai Motors, GS, and KT Corporation. COPA Funds support domestic companies
acquiring overseas businesses and assets.

column38:
